item.title: U.S. Moves to Seize Cryptocurrency Accounts Linked to North Korean Heists
item.description: U.S. authorities said the accounts were used by North Korean hackers who stole an estimated more than a quarter of a billion dollars from exchanges around the world.

item.title: Spain Weighs Legacy of Juan Carlos I After Ex-King Moves to Persian Gulf
item.description: Spain’s former monarch surprised his country this month when he said he was going into exile. His choice of new home has raised eyebrows further: the United Arab Emirates, in the Gulf region where his business dealings triggered the scandals battering his reputation.

item.title: Russian Prosecutors Have No Plans to Investigate Navalny Poisoning
item.description: Russian prosecutors said they don’t have any plans to investigate the suspected poisoning of the Kremlin’s best-known critic, Alexei Navalny, saying there so far is no evidence of a crime being committed.

item.title: China Coast Guard Seizes Hong Kong Activists Fleeing to Taiwan
item.description: China’s coast guard detained a group of Hong Kong activists after intercepting a boat in the South China Sea en route to Taiwan.

item.title: Putin Says Russian Security Team Ready to Aid Belarusian Ally
item.description: Russia has assembled a law enforcement team to help shore up Belarusian leader Alexander Lukashenko if protests against him spiral out of control, President Vladimir Putin said, giving the first indications of how Moscow might intervene to help its longstanding ally.

item.title: Christchurch Mosque Shooter Who Killed 51 Gets Life Imprisonment
item.description: The man who murdered 51 people in live-streamed attacks on two New Zealand mosques was sentenced to life in prison without parole, the first time the country has imposed a punishment that denies any chance of release.
